                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia presents Euler's identity as the equation e^{iπ} + 1 = 0, a special case of Euler’s formula e^{ix} = cos x + i sin x (set x = π) — which gives e^{iπ} = −1, hence e^{iπ} + 1 = 0. It explains this equality can be proved using the exponential and trigonometric power series or by interpreting complex numbers in polar form, and notes the identity is celebrated for linking five fundamental constants (0, 1, π, e, and i) and common operations, often cited as an exemplar of mathematical beauty.",
